## 2 Proposed Method

We consider training a deep neural network that takes an input vector \(\bm{x}\) and produces an output \(f(\bm{\theta},\bm{x})\). With a training set \(\left(\bm{y}_{i},\bm{x}_{i}\right)_{i=1}^{n}\) consisting of \(n\) samples and a loss function \(\ell\), the network parameters \(\bm{\theta}\) are learned by minimizing the empirical loss \(\mathcal{L}\) over the training set:

\[\min_{\bm{\theta}}\mathcal{L}(\bm{\theta}):=\frac{1}{n}\sum\nolimits_{i=1}^{ n}\ell(f(\bm{\theta},\bm{x}_{i}),\bm{y}_{i}).\]

To solve the optimization problem, [10] proposed a full matrix variant of Adagrad, which uses a preconditioner matrix to partially capture the curvature information. Given the stochastic gradient \(\bm{g}_{t}=\nabla\mathcal{L}_{B}(\bm{\theta}_{t})\) where \(\mathcal{L}_{B}\) represents the loss of a sampled mini-batch, the preconditioner \(\bm{H}_{t}\) and the next iterate \(\bm{\theta}_{t+1}\) are computed as follows:

\[\bm{H}_{t}=\bm{H}_{t-1}+\bm{g}_{t}\bm{g}_{t}^{T},\ \ \bm{\theta}_{t+1}=\bm{ \theta}_{t}-\alpha_{t}(\bm{H}_{t}^{1/2}+\epsilon\bm{I})^{-1}\bm{g}_{t},\] (1)

where \(\alpha_{t}\) is the step size and \(\epsilon\) is a small constant introduced for numerical stability. As manipulating the full preconditioner matrix \(\bm{H}_{t}\) is computationally prohibitive, commonly used adaptive optimizers often rely on only the diagonal elements of the preconditioner matrix. Examples include the element-wise version of Adagrad [10] and many of its extensions such as Adam [20].

However, previous studies [16; 23; 1] have shown that in many scenarios, non-diagonal preconditioning can lead to superior results. Hence, it is crucial to design an approximation of the preconditioner that captures more information compared to diagonal Adagrad, while still maintaining practicality for neural network training. This is the primary focus of our paper.

### Block-diagonal Structure of the Preconditioner

Due to the substantial size of the full preconditioner matrix in deep neural networks, it is often impractical to employ it directly. Consequently, in line with the majority of existing literature [16, 23, 1], we precondition each layer separately. This effectively imposes a block diagonal structure assumption on the preconditioner:

\[\bm{H}_{t}=\text{Diag}(\bm{H}_{t}^{1},\dots,\bm{H}_{t}^{L}),\]

where \(L\) is the number of layers. From now on, we will approximate each \(\bm{H}_{t}^{l}\) separately. Therefore, for notational simplicity, we will omit the layer index and refer to the preconditioner matrix for a single layer as \(\bm{H}_{t}\).

Consider a fully connected layer with weights \(\bm{W}\in\mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{in}}\times d_{\text{out}}}\), where \(d_{\text{in}}\) and \(d_{\text{out}}\) represent the number of input and output neurons, respectively. In Transformer networks, these dimensions can extend to thousands, making it impractical to store the full preconditioner \(\bm{H}_{t}\) which has size \(d_{\text{in}}d_{\text{out}}\times d_{\text{in}}d_{\text{out}}\). To address this issue, prior studies have identified a block-diagonal structure in \(\bm{H}_{t}\) and applied a block-diagonal approximation. Specifically, [5, 7] empirically demonstrated that the preconditioner of a fully connected layer exhibits a block-diagonal structure comprising \(d_{\text{out}}\) blocks, each with a size of \(d_{\text{in}}\). In this structure, the weights connecting different input neurons to the same output neuron are grouped together as a block.

We visualize this block-diagonal structure in Figure 1. Specifically, we examine different fully connected layers of a Transformer model and plot the preconditioner using two different orderings: \(\bm{H}_{t}^{\text{in}}\) follows row-major ordering, grouping weights associated with the same input neuron, while \(\bm{H}_{t}^{\text{out}}\) follows column-major ordering, grouping weights associated with the same output neuron. Notably, we observe that \(\bm{H}_{t}^{\text{out}}\) demonstrates a much stronger block-diagonal structure, confirming our choice of block-diagonal approximation.

Although this particular block-diagonal structure has been observed in the literature, to the best of our knowledge, the underlying reason for this block-diagonal structure has not been analyzed mathematically. Here we show that the block-diagonal structure exists based on the following analysis. Assume we compute the preconditioner with a fixed parameter, then we can denote \(\bm{X}\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times d_{\text{in}}}\) as the input of this layer for all the \(n\) samples, and the fully connected layer can be written as

\[\bm{Z}=\bm{X}\bm{W},\]

where \(\bm{W}\in\mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{in}}\times d_{\text{out}}}\) is the weight matrix and \(\bm{Z}\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times d_{\text{out}}}\) is the output matrix. Let \(D_{\bm{W}}=\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\text{vec}(\bm{W})}\) and \(D_{\bm{Z}}=\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\bm{Z}}\) denote the gradients of the loss function with respect to \(\bm{W}\) and \(\bm{Z}\), respectively. Additionally, let us define the preconditioner as:

\[\bm{H}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{H}^{(1,1)}&\dots&\bm{H}^{(1,m)}\\ \vdots&\ddots&\vdots\\ \bm{H}^{(m,1)}&\dots&\bm{H}^{(m,m)}\end{bmatrix},\] (2)

where \(m=d_{\text{out}}\) is the number of blocks. Since \(\bm{H}=D_{\bm{W}}D_{\bm{W}}^{T}\), we can derive the following lemma:

**Lemma 1**: _Assuming the model is evaluated with a fixed parameter \(\theta\), then any two diagonal blocks \(\bm{H}^{(i,i)}\), \(\bm{H}^{(j,j)}\) and two corresponding off-diagonal blocks \(\bm{H}^{(i,j)}\), \(\bm{H}^{(j,i)}\) for the preconditioner matrix of a fully connected layer will satisfy the following inequality:_

\[\|\bm{H}^{(i,i)}\|_{F}^{2}+\|\bm{H}^{(j,j)}\|_{F}^{2}\geq\|\bm{H}^{(i,j)}\|_{ F}^{2}+\|\bm{H}^{(j,i)}\|_{F}^{2}.\] (3)

Figure 1: The second-moment matrices of two different fully connected layers in a Transformer (detailed configurations can be found in our experimental section; details of the visualization can be found in Appendix 6.2). As we can see, \(\bm{H}_{t}^{\text{out}}\) shows a clearer block diagonal structure compared to \(\bm{H}_{t}^{\text{in}}\), verifying our choice of grouping weights by output neurons.

The proof is deferred to the appendix. Based on this lemma, we can conclude that the diagonal blocks have a higher Frobenius norm compared with the corresponding off-diagonal blocks.

However, directly using this block-diagonal structure is impractical for large-scale problems. Since there are \(d_{\text{out}}\) groups and each group has size \(d_{\text{in}}\), storing this block-diagonal approximation requires \(O(d_{\text{in}}^{2}d_{\text{out}})\) memory. To illustrate, a single fully connected layer in a Transformer with \(d_{\text{in}}=4096\) and \(d_{\text{out}}=1024\) (BERT-large) would occupy over 17GB of memory. To address this challenge, [32] proposed a solution by further dividing each block into mini-blocks. On the other hand, [5] explored an alternative approach that enforces all diagonal blocks to be identical for the larger layers. However, they demonstrated that this method adversely affects performance in practice.

### Block Low-rank Approximation with Shared Basis

To simplify notation, we will concentrate on a single layer and omit the layer index moving forward. Let \(\bm{H}_{t}\approx\text{Diag}(\bm{H}_{t}^{(1)},\dots,\bm{H}_{t}^{(m)})\) denotes the block-diagonal approximation of a layer with \(m\) blocks with each block containing \(b=d/m\) variables. For fully connected layers, we use the grouping mentioned in the previous subsection, so \(m=d_{\text{out}}\) and \(b=d_{\text{in}}\), while in general, we let \(m\) be one of the dimensions for other weight tensors. To reduce the memory requirement, we consider an alternative approach to form low-rank approximations for each diagonal block:

\[\bm{B}_{t}^{(i)}\bm{R}_{t}^{(i)}(\bm{B}_{t}^{(i)})^{T}\approx\bm{H}_{t}^{(i)}= \sum\nolimits_{j=1}^{t}\bm{g}_{j}^{(i)}(\bm{g}_{j}^{(i)})^{T},\ \ \ \text{for}\ i=1,\dots,m,\]

where \(k\) is the rank, \(\bm{B}_{t}^{(i)}\in\mathbb{R}^{b\times k}\) and \(\bm{R}_{t}^{(i)}\in\mathbb{R}^{k\times k}\) are the eigenvectors and eigenvalues of each block respectively. Using this approach, the memory cost is reduced to \(\mathcal{O}(dk)\). Nevertheless, this memory cost is still \(k\) times larger than that of first-order optimizers, making it impractical for large-scale training tasks.

We introduce a novel shared-basis approximation scheme to further reduce memory costs. Our key insight is that the diagonal blocks share a similar subspace, which motivates our algorithm to use a joint basis for all the diagonal blocks, thereby reducing memory requirements. To achieve this, we propose the following shared-basis approximation for all the blocks within a single layer:

\[\bm{H}_{t}^{(i)}\approx\bm{B}_{t}\bm{R}_{t}^{(i)}\bm{B}_{t}^{T},\ \ \ \text{for}\ i=1,\dots,m,\] (4)

where \(\bm{B}_{t}\in\mathbb{R}^{b\times k}\) is the orthogonal shared basis and \(\bm{R}_{t}^{(i)}\in\mathbb{R}^{k\times k}\) denotes the coefficients for each block. Note that here we assume each \(\bm{R}_{t}^{(i)}\) is a dense matrix to fully capture the information of each block. This shared-basis approach will reduce the memory complexity to \(O(bk+mk^{2})=O(d_{\text{in}}k+d_{\text{out}}k^{2})\) which can approach the cost of first-order methods when \(k^{2}\leq d_{\text{in}}\) and \(k\leq d_{\text{out}}\). We now give a detailed discussion on this shared-basis block low-rank approximation.

Why can we share basis?To support the idea of this shared-basis approximation, we focus on the analysis of fully connected layers and examine the low-rank approximation of each block. Following the analysis presented in Section 2.1, we consider the form of the preconditioner when evaluated on a fixed parameter \(\theta\). In such cases, each diagonal block can be expressed as:

\[\bm{H}^{(i)}=\bm{X}^{T}(D_{\bm{Z}})_{:,i}((D_{\bm{Z}})_{:,i})^{T}\bm{X}.\]

Therefore, all the diagonal blocks lie in the row space of \(\bm{X}\), the input matrix of a certain layer. Additionally, we observe that in many applications, \(\bm{X}\) tends to occupy a relatively low-rank space. Figure 2 shows the singular value distributions of the intermediate feature \(\bm{X}\) of the Transformer. For all layers, the top \(10\%\) of the rank accounts for over \(80\%\) of the singular values, which suggests \(\bm{X}\) is low rank. This property has also been observed in the literature [6].

If \(\bm{X}\) can be expressed as low-rank decomposition \(\bm{U}\bm{\Sigma}\bm{V}^{T}\) using SVD, where \(\bm{U}\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times k},\bm{\Sigma}\in\mathbb{R}^{k\times k},\bm{V} \in\mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{in}}\times k}\), we have

\[\bm{H}_{t}^{(i,i)}=\bm{V}\bm{\Sigma}\bm{U}^{T}(D_{\bm{Z}})_{:,i}((D_{\bm{Z}})_ {:,i})^{T}\bm{U}\bm{\Sigma}\bm{V}^{T}=\bm{V}\bm{C}_{i}\bm{V}^{T}\]

for every \(i\), which provides an intuition as to why we can share bases for different blocks. We further verify the performance of our proposed basis-sharing approximation is only slightly worse than forming an independent SVD of each diagonal block. We present these experiments in Appendix 6.3.

How to compute the shared basis in the online setting?Given the previous \(\bm{B}_{t-1},\{\bm{R}_{t-1}^{(i)}\}_{i=1}^{m}\) and the current gradient \(\{\bm{g}_{t}^{(i)}\}_{i=1}^{m}\), we will describe the procedure for computing the updated approximate matrices \(\bm{B}_{t},\{\bm{R}_{t}^{(i)}\}_{i=1}^{m}\). Let

\[\bm{M}_{t}^{(i)}\equiv\bm{B}_{t-1}\bm{R}_{t-1}^{(i)}(\bm{B}_{t-1})^{T}+\bm{g}_{ t}^{(i)}(\bm{g}_{t}^{(i)})^{T}\]

be the block to be approximated. To derive the share bases, we concatenate all the blocks

\[\bar{\bm{M}}_{t}=[\bm{M}_{t}^{(1)},\bm{M}_{t}^{(2)},\ldots,\bm{M}_{t}^{(m)}]\]

and compute the SVD to derive its left singular vectors. This is equivalent to computing the top-\(k\) eigenvectors of

\[\bm{A}_{t}\equiv\bar{\bm{M}}_{t}\bar{\bm{M}}_{t}^{T}=\sum\nolimits_{i=1}^{m} \bm{M}_{t}^{(i)}(\bm{M}_{t}^{(i)})^{T}.\]

To efficiently compute the SVD of \(\bm{A}_{t}\), we adopt the randomized SVD method [17]. This approach enables us to compute the basis without explicitly forming \(\bm{A}_{t}\) or any of the \(\bm{M}_{t}^{(i)}\). We initiate the process with an initial matrix \(\bm{Y}\in\mathbb{R}^{b\times(k+p)}\), where \(p\) is the over-sampling constant (we set \(p=0\) in experiments). Iteratively, we perform the following update:

\[\bm{Y}\leftarrow\text{QR}(\bm{A}_{t}\bm{Y}),\] (5)

where \(\text{QR}(\bm{X})\) denotes the QR decomposition of matrix \(\bm{X}\), returning the Q matrix. Using this approach, \(\bm{Y}\) will converge to the dominant eigenspace of \(\bm{A}_{t}\). Additionally, since we can initialize \(\bm{Y}\) with the previous basis, only a few iterations are necessary in practice to obtain an accurate estimation.

Further, we have an improved way to compute the matrix product \(\bm{A}_{t}\bm{Y}\) in (5). The naive way to calculate \(\bm{A}_{t}\bm{Y}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}\bm{M}_{t}^{(i)}(\bm{M}_{t}^{(i)}\bm{Y})\) takes time complexity of \(\mathcal{O}(mbk^{2})=\mathcal{O}(dk^{2})\). However, we can reduce some repeated computations as the blocks share the same basis. Let

\[\bm{p}_{t}^{(i)}\equiv\bm{B}_{t-1}\bm{R}_{t-1}^{(i)}(\bm{B}_{t-1})^{T}\bm{g}_ {t}^{(i)},\]

whose time complexity is \(\mathcal{O}(mbk)=\mathcal{O}(dk)\). We have

\[\sum\nolimits_{i=1}^{m}\bm{M}_{t}^{(i)}(\bm{M}_{t}^{(i)})^{T}\bm{Y} =\bm{B}_{t-1}(\sum\nolimits_{i=1}^{d/b}\bm{R}_{t-1}^{(i)}(\bm{R}_ {t-1}^{(i)})^{T})(\bm{B}_{t-1})^{T}\bm{Y}+\sum\nolimits_{i=1}^{m}\bm{p}_{t}^{( i)}(\bm{g}_{t}^{(i)})^{T}\bm{Y}\] \[+\sum\nolimits_{i=1}^{m}\bm{g}_{t}^{(i)}(\bm{p}_{t}^{(i)})^{T}\bm {Y}+\sum\nolimits_{i=1}^{m}\bm{g}_{t}^{(i)}((\bm{g}_{t}^{(i)})^{T}\bm{g}_{t}^{ (i)})(\bm{g}_{t}^{(i)})^{T}\bm{Y}.\]

Therefore, the time complexity for each power iteration is \(\mathcal{O}(m(k^{3}+bk)+bk^{2})=\mathcal{O}(mk^{3}+dk+bk^{2})\) (the QR decomposition takes \(\mathcal{O}(bk^{2})\) time and is included in this complexity).

